Casual Fans and Bundles
-----------------------

The first thing to note about the new audiobook experience is how much more=
 seamless it is in an App Store world; compare and contrast the current a l=
a carte experience with the new =E2=80=9CIncluded in Premium=E2=80=9D:

There is one particular detail I want to call out: only the image on the ri=
ght includes the =E2=80=9CNow Playing=E2=80=9D bar at the bottom, for the r=
ather obvious reason that I could, with my Spotify subscription, listen to =
the book for =E2=80=9Cfree=E2=80=9D, because I am a Spotify subscriber.

There is, to be sure, consternation amongst some authors and publishers abo=
ut this new model; from the New York Times ( https://www.nytimes.com/2023/1=
0/03/technology/spotify-audiobooks.html ) :

But there=E2=80=99s also concern that Spotify=E2=80=99s plan, which involve=
s experimentation with a new business model for book sales, could upend the=
 lucrative and growing audiobook business. Rather than pay for each audiobo=
ok a customer begins listening to, the company has proposed paying for the =
amount of time that the customer listens, according to a review of a publis=
her=E2=80=99s correspondence with agents, which described the terms. The av=
erage audiobook lasts seven to 10 hours, Spotify said, which means subscrib=
ers can listen to about one and a half books per month, but some popular bo=
oks can run for much longer. Subscribers can sample as many books as they w=
ant, and heavy users who want to listen to more can pay $10.99 for another =
10 hours of audiobook content.

Kim Scott, the best-selling author of =E2=80=9CRadical Candor=E2=80=9D and =
a former executive at Google and Apple, is worried that Spotify=E2=80=99s p=
ay-as-you-listen model could devalue the work that goes into writing a book=
. The proposal that Spotify has advanced is reminiscent of the way Apple ch=
anged the business model of music sales, Ms. Scott said. Rather than buying=
 a full album for $10, iTunes users could buy individual songs for 99 cents=
. =E2=80=9CThis isn=E2=80=99t a launch and iterate moment for the publisher=
s; it=E2=80=99s a Pandora=E2=80=99s box,=E2=80=9D said Ms. Scott, who had d=
eclined when her publisher, St. Martin=E2=80=99s Press, asked to include he=
r book, =E2=80=9CJust Work,=E2=80=9D in Spotify=E2=80=99s streaming service=
. =E2=80=9CBefore I did this deal, I=E2=80=99d hire a consultant and ask, =
=E2=80=98Is this going to bring in new readers or cannibalize existing sale=
s?=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D

At the risk of over-indexing on myself, and with all due respect to Sir Pat=
rick Stewart, I=E2=80=99m not paying $23.90 for his memoir:

At the same time, maybe I=E2=80=99m not such a good example: I buy e-books =
all of the time that I never end of up reading; a consumption-based model w=
ould save me a lot of money!

That=E2=80=99s e-books though; the actual relevant competition is Audible. =
Audible has a =E2=80=9CPlus=E2=80=9D plan for $7.95/month that includes acc=
ess to =E2=80=9Cthousands=E2=80=9D of audiobooks; if you want a title of yo=
ur choice beyond that selection you need to subscribe to the =E2=80=9CPremi=
um Plus=E2=80=9D plan which costs $14.95/month and includes credit for one =
title of your choice a month; there are higher price plans for more credits=
, and you can buy additional credits in packs of three if you are running l=
ow.

Here, once again, we see the power of the App Store: an obvious reason why =
Audible has this convoluted subscription-based credit system is it is the o=
nly way that Audible can ensure its users have a way to =E2=80=9Cbuy=E2=80=
=9D books on their phones (which is the most important device for listening=
 to anything). Once you get past the weird mechanics, though (and the fact =
that you lose your credits if you end your subscription, which is a great c=
hurn-preventer), Audible is still by-and-large selling books a la carte. Yo=
u have to decide you want a particular book, and then buy it.

Spotify=E2=80=99s approach is genuinely new, and I think Scott should be mo=
re optimistic: within a couple of months tens of millions of potential list=
eners to =E2=80=9CJust Work=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 if she chooses to list it =
=E2=80=94 will now be able to listen to it =E2=80=9Cfor free=E2=80=9D, i.e.=
 a part of their subscription. Yes, that does, from a customer perception p=
erspective, =E2=80=9Cdevalue the work that goes into writing a book=E2=80=
=9D; any customer who explicitly chooses to pay for =E2=80=9CJust Work=E2=
=80=9D clearly wants to listen to an audiobook that they expect to be worth=
 their time. What, though, about people who are curious about =E2=80=9CJust=
 Work=E2=80=9D, but aren=E2=80=99t sure if they want to pay the money? Or, =
more expansively, what about people who would have never known that =E2=80=
=9CJust Work=E2=80=9D exists in the first place? Suppose Scott appears on a=
 podcast to talk about her book, and Spotify=E2=80=99s algorithm surfaces t=
he book right underneath the podcast player; this doesn=E2=80=99t happen ye=
t, but I suspect it=E2=80=99s only a matter of time.

In short, what Spotify is proposing is, well, a bundle, and the value of a =
bundle is making content available to people for whom said content is not t=
heir primary preference. Shishir Mehrotra, founder and CEO of Coda (and Spo=
tify board member) explained in his Myths of Bundling ( https://coda.io/@sh=
ishir/four-myths-of-bundling/myth-4-6 ) :

The best bundle is one that minimizes SuperFan overlap and maximizes Casual=
Fan overlap=E2=80=A6this is because bundles are really about providing good=
s for CasualFans=E2=80=A6

This diagram may help visualize. For example, it shows from the bundlers pe=
rspective that Product C is likely adding new customers to BundleY. From a =
consumer=E2=80=99s perspective, if you are a SuperFan of A or B or C, the b=
undle is likely a good deal =E2=80=93 e.g. if you=E2=80=99re a SuperFan of =
A, then you =E2=80=9Cpay for A and get B and C for free=E2=80=9D.

The Four Myths of Bundling ( https://coda.io/@shishir/four-myths-of-bundlin=
g/myth-4-6 )

To take this to a natural extreme, I believe the absolute best world-wide b=
undle would be to design 7 billion unique perfect products for each of the =
7 billion people on the planet, and then set it up in one big bundle. So ev=
eryone gets their perfect product, and also gets access to everyone else=E2=
=80=99s perfect product for free. If there are no CasualFans (i.e. no one e=
lse=E2=80=99s products are any good for me), then this is no worse than eve=
ryone just paying for their own product. But any amount of CasualFan overla=
p will justify the bundling exercise. Fun!

Spotify is only starting with 150,000 titles, but publishers are making a m=
istake if they don=E2=80=99t add more: every title that brings in one new s=
ubscriber is ultimately to the benefit of every other author, albeit only t=
o a point. Note the detail that the number of hours provided is enough for =
1.5 books on average: what the publishers are clearly trying to avoid is gi=
ving =E2=80=9Cwhales=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 listeners who consume multiple audi=
obooks a month =E2=80=94 too good of a deal, and cannibalizing their sales.=
 I understand the limitation =E2=80=94 most people don=E2=80=99t read (or l=
isten), which makes the whales particularly important =E2=80=94 but it does=
 limit some of the potential bundle impact.

That noted, this isn=E2=80=99t just an audiobook bundle, but an audio bundl=
e, broadly speaking (or listening, I should say). Spotify Premium subscribe=
rs are paying for access to music and podcasts, and that represents a massi=
ve growth opportunity for audiobooks, with podcasts, as I noted above, prov=
iding a particularly attractive funnel for authors. To put it in bundling t=
erms, there are now tens of millions of =E2=80=9CCasual Fans=E2=80=9D who h=
ave access to books that, as long as they were sold a la carte, would have =
only ever monetized =E2=80=9CSuper Fans=E2=80=9D.

Spotify=E2=80=99s Goals
---------------

Spotify Chief Business Officer Alex Norstr=C3=B6m was pretty explicit about=
 why this initiative made sense for Spotify at an event the company held in=
 New York City:

( https://videopress.com/embed/t7tBRWPg?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

With Premium, we have created an engine to attract and retain the most pass=
ionate and engaged listeners. 220 million subscribers are paying monthly fo=
r access to Spotify. Now with audiobooks now in Premium we can bring all th=
ese benefits of scale and engagement to authors, publishers, and our subscr=
ibers. If we just make it easier to discover, listen, and share audiobooks,=
 then we believe more people will enjoy them, especially if they don=E2=80=
=99t have to switch apps and buy into a new service. Now by layering in aud=
iobooks, a fast growing and higher margin vertical, we strengthen our busin=
ess, and we help authors grow our reach, and we give our subscribers even m=
ore reason to engage.

Spotify of course gets the obvious benefits of bundling, which is more cust=
omers and, more importantly, lower churn. What makes Spotify an imperfect b=
undler, though, is that they are not buying content wholesale, which would =
make them indifferent to what parts of the bundle are used by customers. Ra=
ther, Spotify pays out based on time, and audiobooks are attractive because=
 their cost per minute is lower than music.

Still, don=E2=80=99t expect this initiative to reduce Spotify=E2=80=99s foc=
us on podcasting: all of the bad press the company has endured recently is =
around the company=E2=80=99s mistaken attempt to pay for exclusive content =
for a category whose entire ethos and, by extension, attractiveness in term=
s of Spotify=E2=80=99s margins, is the fact it is free.

